metadata.name: Ticker Board #44
metadata.description: “Ticker Board” (2022) is the first work released by Figure Frame on FxHash 1.0. It explores the visual structure of information display systems. The grid of animated, over-sized pixels might bring to mind scoreboards, stock exchanges, or departure/arrival listings in an airport terminal. By removing all data from the system, the work highlights the abstract qualities of its underlying framework. The code allows for variations in shape, color, and pixel size. The animated movement of each "Ticker Board" will continue indefinitely.

metadata.name: She speaks in accents #54
metadata.description:
"There is no language that speaks so powerfully to the mind as that of Nature. It is intelligible both to the young and to the old, to the ignorant and to the learned, to the lisping infant as well as to the hoary age, to the untutored savage of the forest as well as to the most favored votary of science." Language of Flowers, 1834

The artwork takes the form of generative botanical compositions and is based on the Victorian Language of Flowers. At the times natural expressions of feelings were frowned upon and highly discouraged, flowers became a communicational tool conveying one's delicate feelings to another, yet in a socially acceptable manner. For successful translation, the interlocutors resorted to publications that collected meanings for each plant and its presentation in a particular context. The piece is based on a range of dictionaries and generates compositions with messages nature carries this season. The materials were picked and scanned by the author. The generative code was written by @neelts

metadata.name: Intricate 4x4 #92
metadata.description:
'Intricated 4x4' was one of the projects that took me the longest to develop. With each WIP, I realized that I could improve some detail, some feature looking for more pleasant, democratic and varied aesthetic results.

This work consists of generating four sets of particles (ellipses or squares) that appear in the four corners of the screen, respecting the predefined margin limits. These sets move towards the center following an attenuated decrease in size thanks to the combination of logarithm and mapping of frameCount and the size variable. This simple trick ensures smoother and less aggressive movements, bringing the observer a sense of tranquility. 

Combining the use of different palettes with some movement conditionals - functions back() and go() - and a charming touch of shading and depth, 'Intricated 4x4' can be considered one of my favorite 
works and I hope it will be for you, after the mint.

Palletes carefully chosen =)

_______________________________
Variability of editions is ensured by:
* 8 background colors
* 13 palettes x 4 colors = 52 colors picked one by one with a lot of care
* possibility to have a fantastic BW version (rarity: 5%)
* possibility to repeat the same palette for both sets (rarity: 8%)
* possibility to have squares intead of circles (rarity: 25%)
* a wide range of Shapes number
* a well thought number of frames, proportional to the total frameCount to make things 'softer'

_______________________________
Interactive instructions:
* Press [S] to save your .png file
* Press [P] to play/pause your animation anytime you like (this increase exponentially your possibilities, right!?)

_______________________________
Creator: Kukuti
May 2022

metadata.name: Stairs #52
metadata.description:
Algorithmically generated stairs. Inspired by Dutch graphic artist M.C. Escher.

Arrangement, style and color set are unique in each edition.

However:
Any edition can generate an infinite amount of arrangements & styles and allows you to cycle through the color sets, so that you can find your perfect piece. 
The preview is based on the initial, randomized arrangement & style.


Created in Vanilla JS on Canvas2D

Controls:
R - Generate Stairs
B - Change Background
C - Change Color
D - Change Style
A - Restart Animation
S - Download Image

metadata.name: Unsolicited abstraction of modern times #193
metadata.description:
This piece is an abstraction and a reflection on the last era, on all that we have built and become. Are we proud of it or has it just been the result of iterating through the days? Since the technology boom, we have experienced great improvements, but perhaps also massive ...mistakes?  

Inspired by textbooks of the 80s, with elements that remind us of industry, technology, networks and systems, "Unsolicited abstraction of modern times" invites us to question our work to date. Has everything really changed?

unknowable 2022




Usage:
press [s] - save pixels (png)
press [p] - save vectors (svg)

metadata.name: Fracture #70
metadata.description:
Fragments of fragments, pieced together.


Please be patient as previews may take a while to generate.
Press 's' in live view to save the current image.
You can modify the URL to specify an image size. Keep in mind that the color palette, styles, and general look of the piece will generally remain the same, but a new image will be created to fit the new dimensions. To do this, add x and y URL parameters to the end of the URL. (Images are created using a pixel ratio of 2, so adding ?x=2560&y1440 to the end of the URL will actually create a 5120x2880 image.)
